  <bp:ProteinReference rdf:ID="ProteinReference30">
    <bp:organism rdf:resource="#BioSource1" />
    <bp:name rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">UniProt:P09486 SPARC</bp:name>
    <bp:name rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">SPARC</bp:name>
    <bp:name rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">ON</bp:name>
    <bp:xref rdf:resource="#UnificationXref210" />
    <bp:comment rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">FUNCTION Appears to regulate cell growth through interactions with the extracellular matrix and cytokines. Binds calcium and copper, several types of collagen, albumin, thrombospondin, PDGF and cell membranes. There are two calcium binding sites; an acidic domain that binds 5 to 8 Ca(2+) with a low affinity and an EF-hand loop that binds a Ca(2+) ion with a high affinity.DEVELOPMENTAL STAGE Expressed at high levels in tissues undergoing morphogenesis, remodeling and wound repair.SIMILARITY Belongs to the SPARC family.</bp:comment>
  </bp:ProteinReference>
