  <bp:ProteinReference rdf:ID="ProteinReference72">
    <bp:organism rdf:resource="#BioSource1" />
    <bp:name rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">UniProt:P19652 ORM2</bp:name>
    <bp:name rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">ORM2</bp:name>
    <bp:name rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">AGP2</bp:name>
    <bp:xref rdf:resource="#UnificationXref365" />
    <bp:comment rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">FUNCTION Functions as transport protein in the blood stream. Binds various hydrophobic ligands in the interior of its beta-barrel domain. Also binds synthetic drugs and influences their distribution and availability. Appears to function in modulating the activity of the immune system during the acute-phase reaction.TISSUE SPECIFICITY Expressed by the liver and secreted in plasma.INDUCTION Synthesis is controlled by glucocorticoids, interleukin-1 and interleukin-6, It increases 5- to 50-fold upon inflammation.DOMAIN Contains a beta-barrel that binds various ligands in its interior.PTM N-glycosylated. N-glycan heterogeneity at Asn-33: Hex5HexNAc4 (minor), Hex6HexNAc5 (major) and dHex1Hex6HexNAc5 (minor).POLYMORPHISM Many different variants of ORM2 are known.SIMILARITY Belongs to the calycin superfamily. Lipocalin family.</bp:comment>
  </bp:ProteinReference>
